r, with previously published biases like the word order correlation bias, and with other biases yet to be invented.
    The competitive linking algorithm can be generalized in various ways.
    New kinds of preexisting knowledge can be exploited to improve accuracy for particular language pairs or even just for particular bitexts.
    It is difficult to say where the greatest advances will come from.
    Yet, one thing is clear from our current vantage point: Research on empirical methods for modeling translational equivalence has not run out of steam, as some have claimed, but has only just begun.
  
  
    Much of this research was performed at the Department of Computer and Information Science at the University of Pennsylvania, where it was supported by an equipment grant from Sun MicroSystems Laboratories and by ARPA Contract #N66001-94C-6043.
    Many thanks to my former colleagues at UPenn and to the anonymous reviewers for their insightful suggestions for improvement.
  

